{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"56fc3ba5-0a08-457f-bbac-e1086bf88ddf","content":"This repo doesn't contain docs on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Run your app** — when it crashes, a `core.<pid>` file appears in `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If no core file appears**, check:\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) can block core dumps for signed/entitled binaries.\n   - The `/cores/` directory must exist and be writable: `sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`\n\n5. **Use macOS Crash Reporter** as an alternative — look for `.ips` crash logs in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n6. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./your-app\n   ```\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, ensure you published with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) so `lldb` can resolve managed frames.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"44e6254a-d5dc-4ee1-b060-2d0dd5eb5671","outputTokens":341},"id":"12a30244-92b8-44c6-831f-8ffc17acf1a3","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:58:34.812Z","parentId":"4016931f-e3c1-4e19-959a-ef02d7c250d2"}
